warnsum.para: This warning summary contains general safety warnings and hazardous materials warnings that must be understood and applied during operation and maintenance of the Expeditionary TRICON Food Sanitation System (ETFSS). Failure to observe these precautions could result in serious injury or death to personnel. Also included are explanations of safety and hazardous materials icons used within this technical manual.

warning.trim.para: All doors and doorways must remain unblocked, both inside and outside, during operation of system to allow for egress during an emergency. Failure to comply may result in serious injury or death to personnel. Seek immediate medical attention if injury occurs.

Interior and exterior areas of ETFSS may be a wet environment. Electrical cables and controls should not be handled with wet hands or while standing in water. Failure to comply may result in serious injury or death to personnel. Seek immediate medical attention if injury occurs.

Power source and ETFSS container must all be grounded to ensure safety of personnel during operation. Operating ETFSS components while ungrounded or improperly grounded may expose personnel to risk of shock resulting in serious injury or death to personnel. Seek immediate medical attention if injury occurs.

High voltage is present during operation. All electrical safety precautions must be followed when operating or maintaining equipment. Failure to comply may result in death or serious injury to personnel. Seek immediate medical attention if exposed to electricity.
Source power must be off prior to connecting or removing power cables to ETFSS shelter.

All jewelry must be removed before starting work. Metal objects, such as rings or tools, can cause short circuits when contacting live circuits. A direct short can cause instant heating of metal resulting in severe burns. Failure to comply may result in serious injury or death to personnel. Seek immediate medical attention if exposed to electricity.

Setup, packout, and some maintenance require climbing and working at elevated levels. Work on ladder or on top of shelter can result in a fall of over 6 ft (1.8 m). Personnel must always maintain a three-point (two hands and a foot, or two feet and a hand) contact on steps, position body near middle of step, and always face shelter while climbing. A spotter should support base while ladder is occupied. Failure to observe safety precautions may result in injury or death to personnel. Seek immediate medical attention if injury occurs.

Floor areas routinely become wet during operation of ETFSS as a result of cleaning, accidental spills, product leaks, or presence of inclement weather conditions. All spills or leaks should be cleaned as soon as possible and movement limited until flooring is dry after every cleaning. Personnel should be mindful of slippery areas and use anti-slip mats where necessary during operation. Failure to comply may result in serious injury to personnel. Seek immediate medical attention if injury occurs.

Cable, hose, and other equipment layout should be accomplished to minimize risk of trip hazards to personnel during operation. Failure to comply may result in injury to personnel. Seek immediate medical attention if injury occurs.

ETFSS equipment must be off and allowed to cool before attempting any maintenance. Failure to comply may result in serious burn injury or death to personnel. Seek immediate medical attention if injury occurs.

Some items covered in this manual require multiple personnel to lift or move. Appropriate number of personnel must be used when moving large, bulky, or heavy items. Attempting to lift these items with fewer than recommended personnel may cause serious injury. Seek immediate medical attention if injury occurs.

Some items covered in this manual are extremely heavy and require material handling equipment (MHE), or other suitable lifting device, to lift or move. These items should not be attempted to move by hand. Personnel must not stand between MHE and item or below item while it is being moved. Serious injury or death to personnel may result if safety precautions are not observed. Seek immediate medical attention if injury occurs.

Use caution with pressurized water systems. Residual pressure must be vented or isolated to prevent release before hoses, fittings, or equipment are connected or disconnected. Failure to comply can result in serious injury to personnel.

Hearing can be permanently damaged if personnel are exposed to constant high noise levels of 85 decibels (dB) or greater. Wear approved hearing protection devices when operating or working within 61 ft (19 m) of MHE when engine is running. Personnel exposed to high noise levels shall participate in a hearing conservation program in accordance with . Hearing loss occurs gradually but becomes permanent over time.

hazard.para: Personnel may be exposed to chemicals or other hazardous materials during cleaning operations. Personnel must wear gloves for protection while performing cleaning procedures. Failure to follow this warning may result in serious illness or death. Seek immediate medical attention if illness occurs.

Wastewater generated during operation may contain biohazardous materials. When maintaining water plumbing or associated components, personnel must wear impermeable gloves, apron, and goggles for protection. Failure to comply can result in serious illness or death to personnel.

Potable water hoses or fittings should not be handled directly after handling wastewater hoses or fittings. Wastewater items may contain bacteria or viruses that present a danger to life or health if not properly sanitized. Seek immediate medical attention if illness occurs.

When using isopropyl alcohol, wear personal protective equipment (safety goggles or full face shield) to prevent injury to eyes or skin. Maintain proper ventilation to prevent inhalation of fumes. Maintain eye-wash and quick-drench facilities in work area.
Do not use diesel fuel, gasoline, or petroleum solvents for cleaning. These items are highly flammable and, if ignited, can cause injury or death to personnel and damage to equipment.

para0.title: HOW TO OBTAIN TECHNICAL MANUALS
para0.para: When a new system is introduced to the Army inventory, it is the responsibility of the receiving units to notify and inform the Unit Publications Clerk that a Technical Manual (TM) is available for the new system. Throughout the life cycle of the new system, the Publications Proponent will also provide updates and changes to the Technical Manual.

To receive new Technical Manuals or change packages to existing Technical Manuals for fielded equipment, provide the Unit Publications Clerk the full Technical Manual number, title, date of publication, and number of copies required. The Unit Publications Clerk will justify the request through the Unit Publications Officer. When the request is approved, is used to order the series of Technical Manuals from the Army Publishing Directorate (APD).

For a first level paragraph, titles are in all upper case/capital letters, e.g., FRONT MATTER. Subordinate paragraph titles will have the first letter of the first word of each principle word all upper case/capital letters, e.g., Manual Organization and Page Numbering System. The location of additional material that must be referenced is clearly marked. Illustrations supporting maintenance procedures/text are located underneath, or as close as possible to, their referenced paragraph.

Each work package is numbered sequentially starting at page 1. The work package has its own page numbering scheme and is independent of the page numbering used by other work packages. Each page of a work package has a page number of the form -YY where is the work package number (e.g. 0010 is work package 10) and YY represents the number of the page within that work package. A page number such as 0010-1/blank means that page 1 contains information but page 2 of that work package has been intentionally left blank.

cpcdata.title: CORROSION PREVENTION AND CONTROL (CPC)
cpcdata.para: Corrosion prevention and control of Army materiel is a continuing concern. It is important that any corrosion problems with this item be reported so that the problem can be corrected and improvements can be made to prevent the problem in future items. The term "corrosion" means the deterioration of a material or its properties due to a reaction of that material with its chemical environment. An example is the rusting of iron.

Corrosion damage in metals can be seen, depending on the metal, as tarnishing, pitting, fogging, surface residue, and/or cracking. Plastics, composites, and rubbers can also degrade (also considered to be corrosion based on the above definition of corrosion). Degradation is caused by thermal (heat), oxidation (oxygen), solvation (solvents), or photolytic (light, typically ultraviolet) processes.

The most common exposures are excessive heat or light. Damage from these processes will appear as cracking, softening, swelling, and/or breaking. The US Army has defined the following nine (9) forms of corrosion used to evaluate the deterioration of metals. These shall be used when evaluating and documenting corrosion.
UNIFORM (or general attack): Affects a large area of exposed metal surface, like rust on steel or tarnish on silver. It gradually reduces the thickness of the metal until it fails.
CREVICE: Occurs in crevices created by rubber seals, gaskets, bolt heads, lap joints, dirt or other surface deposits. It will develop anywhere moisture or other corrosive agents are trapped and unable to drain or evaporate.
SELECTIVE LEACHING: One element, usually the anodic element of an alloy, corrodes away, leaving the cathodic element. This can create holes in metal.
INTERGRANULAR: Metal deterioration caused by corrosion on the bonds between or across the grain boundaries of the metal. The metal will appear to be peeling off in sheets, flaking, or being pushed apart by layers. A particular type of intergranular corrosion is exfoliation.
PITTING: This can result from conditions similar to those for crevice corrosion. Pits can develop on various materials due to their composition. Weapon boxes are big victims of pitting.
EROSION: Results when a moving fluid (liquid or gas) flows across a metal surface, particularly when solid particles are present in the fluid. Corrosion actually occurs on the surface of the metal, but the moving fluid washes away the corrosion and exposes a new metal surface, which also corrodes.
FRETTING: Occurs as a result of small, repetitive movements (e.g., vibration) between two surfaces in contact with each other. It's usually identified by a black powder corrosion product or pits on the surface.
GALVANIC: Occurs when two different types of metal come in contact with each other, like steel bolts on aluminum, for example. This is a common problem on aircraft because of their mix of metals.
STRESS: Term used to describe corrosion cracking and corrosion fatigue.

Where an item is not ready/available due to one of these forms of corrosion, it shall be recorded as a corrosion failure in the inspection record and the appropriate code (170) for corrosion shall be used when requesting/performing maintenance.

If a corrosion problem is identified, it can be reported as an EIR or PQDR. Use of key words such as "corrosion," "rust," "deterioration," or "cracking" will ensure that the information is identified as a CPC problem. should be submitted to the address specified in .

eqpdesc.title: Characteristics
eqpdesc.para:
The Expeditionary TRICON Food Sanitation System (ETFSS) () provides the sanitation capability required to perform clean up following food service operations in the field. ETFSS is housed in a standard TRICON, is moveable using standard forklift pockets, and transportable by land, sea, air, or rail. ETFSS is enclosed in a 6.5-ft (1.98 m) x 8-ft (2.44 m) x 8-ft (2.44 m) TRICON with expandable wings on two sides. The wings are expandable for operation providing approximately three times the floor space of a basic, non-expandable TRICON. ETFSS uses existing Department of Defense inventory components augmented by standard commercial equipment. ETFSS uses the three sink sanitation method with three sinks of water maintained at different temperatures for successive cleaning, rinsing, and sanitizing of pots, pans, and cooking utensils. The water is heated by a Modular Multi-Fuel Burner under each sink. Included in the system are integrated light-emitting diode (LED) light bars, a power distribution panel assembly (PDP) door, integrated plumbing and fuel distribution systems, integrated food waste handling system, and 3,000-gal. (11356.24 L) SOURCE and WASTE water collapsible fabric storage tanks.
ETFSS Deployed

para0.title: Introduction
para0.para: The Expeditionary TRICON Food Sanitation System (ETFSS) () consists of one TRICON and various support items required to provide field kitchen sanitation capabilities for 150 personnel, twice daily. ETFSS theory of operation by major component is described in the following paragraphs.

systhry.title: ETFSS
systhry.para: ETFSS is housed in a modified 6.5-ft (1.98-m) x 8-ft (2.44-m) x 8-ft (2.44-m) ISO TRICON cargo container. Three individually heated sinks, a grease trap & waste tank assembly, two tabletops, and a storage and drying rack assembly are housed within the ETFSS container. The TRICON is equipped with two expandable wings which provide operating floorspace for sanitation and drying of food service equipment. Access to ETFSS is through doors on right wing and rear of shelter. One vent fan and two air intake filters are provided to allow airflow within the TRICON. One exhaust fan and manifold are provided to direct and expel burner exhaust fumes. Two wall mounted space heaters and air conditioners (AC) allow for climate control as needed. A heat trace wire is installed to prevent freezing of internal plumbing.

systhry.title: ETFSS Power
systhry.para: ETFSS is not supplied with power generation equipment and must be used with existing capability (either generator or shore power) from base camp(s) the ETFSS is being utilized to support. ETFSS consists of one power distribution panel mounted on shelter. Distribution panel requires 120/208 VAC, 3 phase, 60 Hz, 60-A, 4 wire power. Power is routed to ETFSS shelter via one run of cables from a base camp power distribution box ().

systhry.title: Power Distribution Panel Assembly
systhry.para: ETFSS power is supplied by one power distribution panel assembly mounted on the front of the shelter (). The ETFSS receives 208 VAC power through 60-A phase A, B, C, neutral, and ground cables. The panel has one 60-A MIL-SPEC power input receptacle, is equipped with four 20-A output receptacles which provide power to cold weather equipment and a MAIN circuit breaker controlling power flow to all branch circuits on the panel. Each branch circuit is listed on the inside of the door panel.

systhry.title: Lighting System
systhry.para: ETFSS lighting is provided by two permanently-mounted 4-ft lighting fixtures (includes white and blackout lighting) found in the center area of the shelter (). Lighting controls are found on the raceway mounted next to rear door.

figure.title: ETFSS Lighting System - Top Down View

systhry.title: Sink with Burner
systhry.para: Each sink utilizes heat from a fuel-fired burner, housed within its stainless steel heating cabinet, to heat a holding tank that is filled with water. The sink controller controls the temperature of the sink by receiving input from the water temperature thermocouple and the low-level thermocouple. Once operational, the emissions from the burner are expelled through the exhaust vent. The sink is equipped with a water level sensor to ensure enough water is in the holding tank, therefore preventing overheating. If the water level sensor senses low water, the burner is disabled. Water is drained from the holding tank through a single, manually operated drain valve.
The sinks are each equipped with an exhaust thermocouple which monitors exhaust temperature to prevent overheating.
The sinks are each mounted to a locking mechanism, which has wheels and thumbscrews, allowing it to be secured to the locking plate on the floor ().

systhry.title: Emergency Stop (E-Stop)
systhry.para: The e-stop safety circuit consists of a push-button switch , an exhaust fan, a differential pressure switch , and three ground-fault circuit interrupters (GFCI) mounted on the raceway.
The e-stop switch provides the operator with the ability to cut power to the burners remotely.
The differential pressure switch is tied to the exhaust fan to prevent burner operation in the event of insufficient exhaust airflow.

Additionally, the following conditions must be met before engaging the burners:
Container exterior vents open to ensure sufficient airflow to close exhaust fan differential pressure switch
Exhaust fan switch ON and exhaust fan operating.
E-stop switch disengaged (out).
Raceway mounted burner GFCI must be reset (green light will be illuminated).

systhry.title: Source and Waste Water System
systhry.para: Potable water is supplied by a 3,000-gal (11356 L) SOURCE water bag connected to the shelter. Two supply pumps inside the shelter distribute water to necessary components via shelter plumbing. Drains collect wastewater and deliver it to grease intercepter assembly to separate solids from liquids. A sump pump housed within the waste tank assembly delivers wastewater to a 3,000-gal (11356 L) WASTE water bag.

systhry.title: ETFSS Plumbing
systhry.para: Water enters ETFSS shelter via a 1-1/2-inch cam and groove fitting located on rear of shelter. Water is then routed to a tee and through two supply pumps for delivery to ETFSS components (). Power to pumps is controlled by a dedicated 20-A circuit breaker. Water output from the pumps is routed through a series of tee fittings and hoses to the fixed sink faucets, the pressure tank, and the solenoid valve. The solenoid valve controls water supply to a tee, which splits to the half-inch foot valve and the transfer pump. The transfer pump routes water through the foot valve to the sill faucet. A three-way momentary switch controls power and priming for transfer pump. Each sink well has an individually controlled drain to evacuate water. These drains are connected in series and wastewater flows to the grease intercepter and waste tank assembly.

SOURCE water inlet connection and WASTE water outlet connection are found on the front of the ETFSS under the distribution box (). Source inlet port is 1-1/2 inches and WASTE water outlet port is 2 inches. Internal plumbing is permanently mounted to the wall of the TRICON behind the backsplash assembly. Three movable deep sink assemblies are located in front of the electrical/plumbing installation. A manifold mounted under the sink allows flow to the sink.

systhry.title: Grease Intercepter & Waste Tank Assembly
systhry.para: Wastewater drains from the sinks towards the grease intercepter & waste tank assembly () through a 1-1/4-in drain hose connected to Sink 1 drain valve, and enters grease intercepter through port on inlet side where it flows into grease separation cavity. As wastewater cools, solids sink to bottom of trap and fats, oils, and grease float to top. A sump pump is located in waste tank with a float switch that automatically runs pump when water level reaches 7 to 10 inches (17.8 to 25.4 cm) and shuts off when water level reaches 2 to 5 inches (5.1 to 12.7 cm). Wastewater is pumped through outlet fitting toward WASTE water bag.

systhry.title: Source Fuel System
systhry.para: ETFSS has an integrated source fuel system (). A SOURCE fuel inlet Quick-Disconnect (QD) fitting is located in the ETFSS I/O Pan. Fuel is supplied to the system from a suitable container. Two 5.28 gal (20 L) fuel containers are provided as optional containers. The fuel container is then fitted with a removable fuel adapter. Fuel flows from the source, through the shelter to the fuel filter via hoses, then through two separate manifolds for distribution to the burner units in each sink.

systhry.title: Return Fuel System
systhry.para: ETFSS has an integrated return fuel system (). A return fuel outlet connection is located in the ETFSS I/O Pan. Fuel return flows from the burner units through hoses to manifolds and a tee and out of the shelter to the fuel container.

wpidinfo.title: DESCRIPTION AND USE OF OPERATOR CONTROLS AND INDICATORS

para0.title: Introduction
para0.para: This work package provides descriptions and locations of Expeditionary TRICON Food Sanitation System (ETFSS) controls and indicators. Personnel operating ETFSS should know location and proper use of every control and indicator.

wpidinfo.title: OPERATION UNDER USUAL CONDITIONSPREPARATION FOR USE - SITING REQUIREMENTS

warning.trim.para: Expeditionary TRICON Food Sanitation System (ETFSS) weighs approximately 7,500 lb (3,401 kg) and must only be moved using MHE of sufficient weight capacity. Care should be used at all times when lifting and moving container. ETFSS must only be moved when their expandable sections are fully stowed and secured for transport. Failure to comply may result in injury to personnel. Seek immediate medical attention if injured.

caution.trim.para: ETFSS should be situated on firm, well-drained ground, with a slope of less than 5% (a 12 in (30.5 cm) rise over 20 ft (6.1 m)) or less.
ETFSS must only be moved when all cargo and rear doors are closed, and its expandable sections are fully stowed and secured for transport. Failure to comply may result in equipment damage.

note.trim.para: For placement, use MHE. Take note of container's two sets of forklift pockets: Standard pockets (on all containers): 14-1/2 in (36.8 cm) on 82 in (208.3 cm) centers.

specpara.para:
Ensure site for deploying ETFSS meets following requirements:
Firm ground, with good water drainage away from ETFSS and corner jacks.
Generally flat and level, with a slope of less than 5% (a 12 in (30.5 cm) rise over a 20 ft (6.1 m) run) or less.
Free of large rocks, trees, or sunken soil.
Large enough to accommodate footprint of deployed ETFSS (20 ft (6.1 m) x 6.5 ft (2.0 m)).

note.trim.para: Before placing and setting up ETFSS, give attention to possible siting locations of other Expeditionary TRICON System shelters, or support equipment such as water tanks, water heaters, pumps, and electrical generators.

specpara.para: Position ETFSS so its end walls are perpendicular to ground slope.

Raise ETFSS only enough to place blocking under each corner fitting .
Place appropriate thickness blocking under each corner fitting so that when ETFSS is lowered it will be level in both directions.
Lower MHE and observe bubble levels located on all four container exterior walls. Ensure bubbles are within indicator marks.
Repeat until unit is level.

proc.title: General
proc.para: This work package contains instructions for safely operating ETFSS under unusual conditions. In addition to normal preventive maintenance service, special care must be taken to keep ETFSS operational in extreme weather conditions.

proc.title: Operation on Sloped Terrain
proc.para: ETFSS must be operated on firm ground with a 5 slope or less. If terrain requires that ETFSS be set up on un-level ground, extra steps are required to ensure unit will be stable during use. Follow guidance in Siting Requirements () to properly orient and support ETFSS for deployment and operation.

proc.title: Operation in Cold
proc.para: ETFSS can be operated in conditions down to 40 °F (4.4 °C) with no special precautions. If ETFSS is deployed when temperatures are expected to drop below 40 °F (4.4 °C), special care must be taken to prevent freeze damage to water system and waste system. This will include either draining water supply and waste collection systems or use of Cold Weather Equipment (CWE) on ETFSS piping, pumps, and storage bags.

proc.title: Operation in Extreme Cold
proc.para: Care must be taken when handling electrical cables. Extreme cold weather can cause insulation material on electrical wire to crack, causing short circuits. Water hoses and other materials can also become hard, brittle, and easily damaged. Do not allow ice and snow to build up on TRICON roof or expanded section roof. Place a footing of planks or brush under wing support jacks to keep them from freezing to ground.

proc.title: Storage in Cold
proc.para: Prior to placing ETFSS into storage, water system and waste collection system must be drained following guidance provided in Preparation for Movement (), (), (), (), and (). Even if temperatures are not currently below 33 °F (.56 °C), it is possible that temperatures will drop that low before ETFSS is used again. This will prevent freeze damage to piping and components in water system and waste system.
Planks should be placed under corner fittings. Do not allow ice and snow to build up on roof.

proc.title: Operation in Extreme Heat
proc.para: Use of right and rear doors should be kept to a minimum. Water system does not cool. Minimum water temperature will be at or slightly higher than water temperature at source.

proc.title: Operation in Sandy Or Dusty Areas
proc.para: When operating in sandy or dusty areas, perform Preventive Maintenance Checks and Services (PMCS) () monthly checks on a weekly interval, and keep use of ingress/egress doors to a minimum. Make sure power distribution panel assembly (PDP) door is kept closed.

proc.title: Operation in High Winds
proc.para: Keep all loose objects secured or stowed. Outer doors can be restrained by ratchet straps.

proc.title: Operation in Rain
proc.para: When rain is expected, a drain trench should be dug around ETFSS outside perimeter to collect and drain water away. Make sure PDP door is kept closed.

proc.title: Operation in Freezing Rain and Snow
proc.para: ETFSS operation can operate properly during freezing rain or snow. Do not let snow accumulate on ETFSS or associated hardware. Use caution when removing snow from power cables and near power receptacles. Make sure PDP door is closed, and ensure all outlets are not exposed to freezing rain or snow.

proc.title: Operation in High Altitude
proc.para: Adjust air damper on Burner, multi-fuel, modular, when operating ETFSS at high altitude. If ETFSS is being powered by a generator, generator may suffer engine performance and output power degradation at altitudes above 7,500 ft. (2286 m). In this instance verify that all devices being powered by generator do not collectively exceed generators de-rated output level.

step1.para: Remove burner () IAW .
Notify maintainer to perform adjustments to the modular burner to conform to altitudinal conditions.
Install burner () IAW .

geninfo.title: GENERAL
geninfo.para: This chapter provides operator and maintainer maintenance information and includes troubleshooting maintenance procedures. Troubleshooting instructions covered in this section are unique to Expeditionary TRICON Food Sanitation System (ETFSS).

Troubleshooting index lists common malfunctions that may occur during ETFSS shelter inspection and operation. Find malfunction to be eliminated and go to indicated troubleshooting work package that follows. Index cannot list all malfunctions that may occur, all tests or inspections needed to find fault, nor all actions required to correct fault. If existing malfunction is not listed, or cannot be corrected through this troubleshooting index, notify next higher level of maintenance.

geninfo.title: GENERAL INFORMATION
geninfo.para: This work package describes the operator testing and troubleshooting process used to perform troubleshooting on the Expeditionary TRICON Food Sanitation System (ETFSS) and includes information on the methods used to perform troubleshooting.

para0.title: GENERAL
para0.para: The troubleshooting procedures contained in this chapter list the symptoms, malfunctions, and corrective actions required to return the ETFSS to normal operation. Perform the steps in the order they appear in the work packages.
DO NOT START THE TASK UNTIL: The task is understood. The personnel, materials, replacement parts, and/or testing equipment for the task are prepared.

All ETFSS fault conditions can be found in the troubleshooting index work package (). The reader will be directed to the appropriate work package to begin the troubleshooting process. The fault condition will be listed in the work package as a symptom with one or more possible malfunctions. Each malfunction will have one or more corrective actions to be performed. After each corrective action is completed, attempt to operate the equipment to see if the fault is corrected.

para0.title: TROUBLESHOOTING INDEX
para0.para: The troubleshooting index () is listed by subsystem in alphabetical order. Each symptom under the applicable subsystem will be listed in alphabetical order. Symptoms in the indicated work packages will also appear in alphabetical order.

The troubleshooting index lists common malfunctions that may occur during ETFSS inspection and operation. Find the malfunction to be addressed and go to the indicated troubleshooting work package. The troubleshooting index cannot list all malfunctions that may occur, all tests or inspections needed to find the fault, nor all actions required to correct the fault. If the existing malfunction is not listed, or cannot be corrected through this troubleshooting index, notify your supervisor.

An example of the troubleshooting process is shown below. The symptom describes the problem being experienced. The malfunction is the cause of the symptom starting with the most likely cause or most easily remedied. Further malfunctions will describe alternate fault conditions. The corrective action shows the steps required to correct each malfunction.

para0.title: SYMPTOM
para0.para: No power to TRICON shelter.

para0.title: MALFUNCTION
para0.para: Power cable unplugged.

para0.title: CORRECTIVE ACTION
para0.para: STEP 1. Verify power cable is connected securely to power input receptacle.
STEP 2. Verify power cable is securely connected at the source and the source is energized.
STEP 3. Reset external power control circuit breaker by setting to OFF, then back to ON.

wpidinfo.title: PREVENTIVE MAINTENANCE CHECKS AND SERVICES (PMCS) INTRODUCTION

para0.title: GENERAL
para0.para: A Preventive Maintenance Checks and Services (PMCS) table is provided in . Following procedures in table ensures equipment is kept in good operating condition and ready for its primary mission.

Always observe WARNINGS and CAUTIONS appearing in PMCS tables. WARNINGS and CAUTIONS appear before applicable procedures. These WARNINGS and CAUTIONS must be observed to prevent serious personal injury or to prevent equipment damage.

para0.title: INTRODUCTION
para0.para: PMCS are performed to keep Expeditionary TRICON Food Sanitation System (ETFSS) in good operating condition and ready for its primary mission. Checks are used to find, correct, and report problems. PMCS is performed every day ETFSS is in operation, and is done according to PMCS table provided. Pay attention to WARNING, CAUTION, and NOTE statements. A WARNING indicates that someone could be hurt or killed. A CAUTION indicates that equipment could be damaged. A NOTE may make your maintenance or repair task easier.
Be sure to perform scheduled PMCS. Always perform PMCS in same order so it becomes a habit. With practice, you will quickly recognize problems with equipment.
Use or , to record any discovered faults. Do not record faults that you fix.

para0.title: PMCS PROCEDURES
para0.para: Tables in list inspections and care required to be performed by operator to keep your equipment in good operating condition. It is arranged so that you can perform operational checks as you walk around equipment.
Tables in list inspections and care required to be performed by maintainer.
Tables in list inspections and care required to be performed by operator to keep Burner, Gas Heating in good operating condition.

subpara1.title: Item Number
subpara1.para: Indicates reference number. When completing or , include item number for item to check/service indicating a fault. Item numbers appear in the order you must perform checks/services listed.

subpara1.title: Interval
subpara1.para: Indicates when you must perform procedure in procedure column.

subpara1.title: Item to Check/Service
subpara1.para: Indicates item to be checked or serviced.

subpara1.title: Procedure
subpara1.para: Indicates procedure you must perform on the item listed in Item to Check/Service column. You must perform procedure at time specified in Interval column.

subpara1.title: Equipment Not Ready / Available If:
subpara1.para: Indicates faults which will prevent your equipment from performing its primary mission. If you perform procedures listed in Procedure column which show faults listed in this column, do not operate equipment. Follow standard procedures for maintaining equipment or reporting equipment failure.

subpara1.title: Other special entries
subpara1.para: Observe all special information and notes that appear in PMCS tables.

subpara1.title: Cleaning
subpara1.para: Proper cleaning of ETFSS and its components is an integral part of maintenance. It helps prevent possible problems in the future, so make it a habit to clean ETFSS and its components whenever necessary.

subpara1.title: Corrosion Prevention and Control (CPC)
subpara1.para: Corrosion Prevention and Control (CPC) of Army materiel is a continuing concern. It is important that any corrosion problems with this item be reported so that problem can be corrected and improvements can be made to prevent problems in future items. Items that are non-mission capable as a result of corrosion shall be recorded as corrosion failure using code 170. Corrosion specifically occurs with metals. It is an electro-chemical process that causes degradation of metals. It is commonly caused by exposure to moisture, acids, bases, or salts. An example is the rusting of iron.

Corrosion damage in metals can be seen, depending on metal, as tarnishing, pitting, fogging, surface residue, and/or cracking. Plastics, composites, and rubbers can also degrade. Degradation is caused by thermal (heat), oxidation (oxygen), solvation (solvents), or photolytic (light, typically UV) processes. Most common exposures are excessive heat or light. Damage from these processes will appear as cracking, softening, swelling, and/or breaking. should be submitted to address specified in . Refer to for full list of corrosion definitions.

subpara1.title: Fluid Leakage
subpara1.para: It is necessary for you to know how fluid leakage affects status of Cold Weather Equipment (CWE). Following are types/classes of leakage you need to know to be able to determine status of CWE. Learn these leakage definitions and remember: when in doubt, notify your supervisor. Equipment operation is allowed with minor leakage (Class I or II). Consideration must be given to fluid capacity in item/system being checked/inspected. When in doubt, notify your supervisor.

When operating with Class I or II leaks, check fluid levels more frequently than required in PMCS. Class III leaks should be reported immediately to your supervisor.
Class I. Seepage of fluid (as indicated by wetness or discoloration) but not great enough to form drops.
Class II. Leakage of fluid great enough to form drops, but not enough to cause drops to drip from item being checked/inspected.
Class III. Leakage of fluid great enough to form drops that fall from item being checked/inspected.

step2.para: If there is no continuity, proceed to .

step2.para: If continuity is found, proceed to .

proc.title: Initial Shipment
proc.para: Initial packaging and shipping of Expeditionary TRICON Food Sanitation System (ETFSS) are responsibility of item manufacturers, who are required to comply with federal and military packing specifications, as stipulated in contractual agreements. ETFSS are normally shipped to depot activities, by domestic freight or parcel post, and packed to comply with overseas shipping requirements. Except for those systems that are unpackaged and subjected to random inspections or testing by depot activity, ETFSS received by a using unit will be contained in original packaging materials.

proc.title: Shipping Between Maintenance Activities
proc.para: Shipping of ETFSS between activities will be accomplished on a signature verification basis using whatever means of military transportation is available. Used ETFSS and other items will be tagged IAW , and rolled, folded, or placed loosely in a pack, bag, or other suitable container, as required. Unused ETFSS will be transported in original shipping containers. During shipment, every effort will be made to protect ETFSS from weather elements, dust, dirt, oil, grease, and acids. Vehicles used to transport ETFSS will be inspected to ensure items are protected from previously cited material damaging conditions.

note.trim.para: Blind rivets are used in locations where only one side of area to be worked on is accessible. Type of rivets used in Expeditionary TRICON Food Sanitation System (ETFSS) are described in and . Additional sizes can be found in if required.
Rivets required to perform maintenance are listed in initial setup of each WP. Use RPSTL to verify identity and location of rivet(s) being replaced.
Materials are listed by body / mandrel. AL is aluminum, ST is carbon steel, CRES is corrosion-resistant steel.

warning.trim.para: Drilling creates metal chips that may enter eyes and cause serious injury. Eye protection and work gloves are required. Failure to comply may result in injury to personnel. Seek immediate medical attention if injury occurs.
Drilling may create a loud noise hazard which may cause permanent hearing loss over time. Hearing protection is required.

caution.trim.para: Be mindful of equipment behind area where drilling will occur. Use of a drill stop is suggested, but not required. Tape may be used on drill bit to mark depth. Failure to comply may result in equipment damage.

note.trim.para: When drilling through rivet head, be careful to avoid enlarging hole in structure. Drill must be operated at a lower speed setting, kept perpendicular to material being drilled, and excessive pressure must not be applied on drill, or new rivets will be too loose.

specpara.para: Drill through head of rivet only, using hole in rivet as a guide. Use proper drill size from .

step1.para: Pry off rivet head ().

caution.trim.para: Do not push rivet shank out by hitting pin punch with a tool.

specpara.para: Push out rivet shank ().

note.trim.para: When installing new rivets in same location as a rivet that has been removed, if diameter of hole in structure has been enlarged during removal of rivet, use next larger diameter rivet for replacement. Material and grip range should remain same.

specpara.para: Determine type, size, and grip range of rivet to be used ().

step1.para: Remove all metal chips and burrs from drilled holes as required.
Insert rivet in hole. Make sure sheets are held tightly together before upsetting or pulling rivet.
Select proper pulling head for rivet being installed, and install pulling head on riveter.
Insert stem of rivet into pulling head ().
Have pulling head parallel to axis of rivet, upset rivet. Exert firm pressure but do not bend or buckle metal. Stem will break off below rivet head surface. No trimming should be required.

Ensure riveted parts are not loose, rivet does not rotate, and rivet head is seated tightly against riveted surface. If rivet is loose or improperly installed, remove rivet IAW this WP and repeat previous steps.

authorize_to_destroy.title: AUTHORITY TO DESTROY
authorize_to_destroy.para: Authorization. Only division or higher commanders have authority to order destruction of equipment. They may however, delegate this authority to subordinate commanders when situation demands it.

report_destruct.title: Reporting Destruction
report_destruct.para: Report any destruction activity through command channels.

para0.title: General Destruction Information
para0.para: Expeditionary TRICON Food Sanitation System (ETFSS) does not contain classified equipment. Refer to Procedures for "Destruction of Equipment to Prevent Enemy Use" for additional guidance.
In the situation where ETFSS must be destroyed, it can be destroyed via burning, explosives, burying, or any other means that would render it unusable for enemy.

randlist.item: Methods of Destruction. Choose methods of destruction which will cause such damage that it will be impossible to restore equipment to a usable condition within combat zone.
Classified Equipment. Classified equipment must be destroyed to such a degree as to prevent duplication by, or revealing means of operation or function to enemy.

Associated Classified Documents. Any classified documents, notes, instructions, or other written material pertaining to function, operation, maintenance, or employment, including drawings or parts lists, must be destroyed in a manner to render them useless to enemy.

wpidinfo.title: REPAIR PARTS AND SPECIAL TOOLS LIST (RPSTL) INTRODUCTION

para0.title: SCOPE
para0.para: This RPSTL lists authorized spares and repair parts; special tools; special test, measurement, and diagnostic equipment (TMDE); and other special support equipment required for performance of field maintenance of Expeditionary TRICON Food Sanitation System (ETFSS). It authorizes requisitioning, issue, and disposition of spares, repair parts, and special tools as indicated by source, maintenance, and recoverability (SMR) codes.

para0.title: GENERAL
para0.para:
In addition to Introduction work package, this RPSTL is divided into following work packages.
Repair Parts List Work Packages. Work packages containing lists of spare and repair parts authorized for use in performance of maintenance at levels determined by MAC/SMR code. These work packages also include parts which must be removed for replacement of authorized parts. Parts lists are composed of functional groups in ascending alphanumeric sequence, with parts in each group listed in ascending figure and item number sequence. Sending units, brackets, filters, and bolts are listed with component they mount on. Bulk materials are listed by item name in Bulk Items work package which follows last Parts List work package. Repair parts kits are listed at end of individual work packages. Repair parts kits for reparable special tools are also listed in a separate work package. Items listed are shown on associated illustrations.
Bulk Items Work Package. This work package lists all items identified as ‘bulk’ in parts lists. Due to nature of bulk items, this work package does not include a Figure.
Special Tools List Work Packages. This work package lists those special tools, special TMDE, and special support equipment authorized by this RPSTL (as indicated by Basis of Issue (BOI) information in DESCRIPTION AND USABLE ON CODE (UOC) column). Tools that are components of common tool sets and/or Class VII are not listed.
Cross-Reference Indexes Work Packages. There are two cross-reference indexes work packages in this RPSTL. National Stock Number (NSN) Index work package refers you to Figure and item number for each NSN listed in RPSTL. Part Number Index work package refers you to figure and item number for each part number listed in RPSTL.

para0.title: EXPLANATION OF COLUMNS IN REPAIR PARTS LIST AND SPECIAL TOOLS LIST WORK PACKAGES
para0.para: ITEM NO. (Column 1). Indicates number used to identify items called out in illustration.

SMR CODE (Column 2). SMR code containing supply/requisitioning information, maintenance level authorization criteria, and disposition instruction, as shown in following breakout. This entry may be subdivided into 4 subentries, one for each service. SMR Code Explanation
Source Code
XX
Maintenance Code
XX
Recoverability Code
X
1st twopositions:How to get an item. 3rd position:Who can install,replace, or use item. 4th position:Who can docomplete repairon item. 5th position:Who determinesdisposition action onunserviceable items.

note.trim.para: Complete Repair: Maintenance capacity, capability, and authority to perform all corrective maintenance tasks of "Repair" function in a use/user environment in order to restore serviceability to a failed item.

para0.para: Source Code. Source code tells you how you get an item needed for maintenance, repair, or overhaul of an end item/equipment. Explanations of source codes follow:

row.entry: Stock items, use applicable NSN to requisition/request items with these source codes. They are authorized to level indicated by code entered in third position of SMR code. Items coded PC are subject to deterioration.

Items with these codes are not to be requested/requisitioned individually. They are part of a kit that is authorized to maintenance level indicated in third position of SMR code. Complete kit must be requisitioned and applied.

Items with these codes are not to be requisitioned/requested individually. They must be made from bulk material which is identified by part number in DESCRIPTION AND USABLE ON CODE (UOC) entry and listed in bulk material group work package of RPSTL. If item is authorized to you by third position code of SMR code, but source code indicates it is made at higher level, order item from higher level of maintenance.

Items with these codes are not to be requested/requisitioned individually. Parts that make up assembled item must be requisitioned or fabricated and assembled at level of maintenance indicated by source code. If third position of SMR code authorizes you to replace item, but source code indicates item is assembled at a higher level, order item from higher level of maintenance.
Do not requisition an "XA" coded item. Order next higher assembly. (Refer to NOTE below.)
If an item is not available from salvage, order it using CAGEC and P/N.
Installation drawings, diagrams, instruction sheets, field service drawings; identified by manufacturer's P/N.
Item is not stocked. Order an XD-coded item through local purchase or normal supply channels using CAGEC and P/N given, if no NSN is available.

note.trim.para: Cannibalization or controlled exchange, when authorized, may be used as a source of supply for items with above source codes except for those items source coded "XA" or those aircraft support items restricted by requirements of .

para0.para: Maintenance Code. Maintenance code tell you level(s) of maintenance authorized to use and repair support items. Maintenance codes are entered in third and fourth positions of SMR code as follows:

Third Position. Maintenance code entered in third position tells you lowest maintenance class authorized to remove, replace, and use an item. Maintenance code entered in third position will indicate authorization to following classes of maintenance:
Maintenance Code
Application/Explanation
C -
Crew
F -
Maintainer maintenance can remove, replace, and use item.
H -
Below Depot Sustainment maintenance can remove, replace, and use item.
L -
Specialized repair activity can remove, replace, and use item.
G -
Afloat and ashore intermediate maintenance can remove, replace, and use item. (Navy only).
K -
Contractor facility can remove, replace, and use item.
Z -
Item is not authorized to be removed, replaced, or used at any maintenance level.
D -
Depot can remove, replace, and use item.

note.trim.para: Army will use C in third position. However, for joint service publications, other services may use O.

para0.para: Fourth Position. Maintenance code entered in fourth position tells you whether or not item is to be repaired and identifies lowest maintenance class with capability to do complete repair (perform all authorized repair functions).

row.entry: Crew (operator) is lowest class that can do complete repair.
Maintainer is lowest class that can do complete repair of item.
Below Depot Sustainment is lowest class that can do complete repair of item.
Specialized repair activity is lowest class that can do complete repair of item
Depot is lowest class that can do complete repair of item.
Both afloat and ashore intermediate levels are capable of complete repair of item. (Navy only)
Complete repair is done at contractor facility.
No repair is authorized. No parts or special tools are authorized for maintenance of "B" coded item. However, item may be reconditioned by adjusting, lubricating, etc., at user level.

para0.para:
Recoverability Code. Recoverability codes are assigned to items to indicate disposition action on unserviceable items. Recoverability code is shown in fifth position of SMR code as follows:
RecoverabilityCode
Application/Explanation
Z -
Nonrepairable item. When unserviceable, condemn and dispose of item at level of maintenance shown in third position of SMR code.
F -
Reparable item. When uneconomically reparable, condemn and dispose of item at field level.
H -
Reparable item. When uneconomically reparable, condemn and dispose of item at below depot sustainment.
D -
Reparable item. When beyond lower level repair capability, return to depot. Condemnation and disposal of item are not authorized below depot.
L -
Reparable item. Condemnation and disposal not authorized below Specialized Repair Activity (SRA).
A -
Item requires special handling or condemnation procedures because of specific reasons (such as precious metal content, high dollar value, critical material, or hazardous material). Refer to appropriate manuals/directives for specific instructions.
G -
Field level reparable item. Condemn and dispose at either afloat or ashore intermediate levels. (Navy only)
K -
Reparable item. Condemnation and disposal to be performed at contractor facility.
NSN (Column (3)). NSN(s) for item is listed in this column.
CAGEC (Column (4)). Commercial and Government Entity Code (CAGEC) is a five-digit code which is used to identify manufacturer, distributor, or Government agency/activity that supplies item.

PART NUMBER (Column (5)). Indicates primary number used by manufacturer (individual, company, firm, corporation, or Government activity), which controls design and characteristics of item by means of its engineering drawings, specifications, standards, and inspection requirements to identify an item or range of items.

note.trim.para: When you use an NSN to requisition an item, item you receive may have a different part number from number listed.

para0.para:
DESCRIPTION AND USABLE ON CODE (UOC) (Column (6)). This column includes following information:
Federal item name, and when required, a minimum description to identify item.
Part numbers of any bulk materials required if item is to be locally manufactured or fabricated.
Hardness Critical Item (HCI). Items that require special handling or procedures to ensure protection against electromagnetic pulse (EMP) damage are marked with letters ‘HCI.’
Statement END OF FIGURE appears below last item description in column (6) for each Figure in repair parts list, special tools repair parts, kits, bulk items, and special tools list work packages.
Refer to Usable on Code details presented later in this work package under SPECIAL INFORMATION.

QTY (Column (7)). QTY (quantity per Figure) column indicates quantity of item used in breakout shown on illustration/Figure. A "V" appearing in this column instead of a quantity indicates that quantity is variable and quantity may change from application to application.

para0.title: EXPLANATION OF CROSS-REFERENCE INDEXES WORK PACKAGES FORMAT AND COLUMNS

seqlist.item:
National Stock Number (NSN) Index Work Package. NSN's in this index are listed in National Item Identification Number (NIIN) sequence.
STOCK NUMBER Column. This column lists NSN in NIIN sequence. NIIN consists of last nine digits of NSN. When using this column to locate an item, ignore first four digits of NSN. However, complete NSN should be used when ordering items by stock number.
For example, if NSN is 5385-01-574-1476, NIIN is 01-574-1476.
FIG. Column. This column lists number of Figure where item is identified/located. Figures are in numerical order in repair parts list and special tools list work packages.
ITEM Column. Item number identifies item associated with Figure listed in adjacent FIG. column. This item is also identified by NSN listed on same line.

Part Number (P/N) Index Work Package. P/Ns in this index are listed in ascending alphanumeric sequence (vertical arrangement of letter and number combinations which places first letter or digit of each group in order A through Z, followed by numbers 0 through 9 and each following letter or digit in like order.)
PART NUMBER Column. Indicates P/N assigned to item.
FIG. Column. This column lists number of Figure where item is identified/located in repair parts list and special tools list work packages.
ITEM Column. Item number is number assigned to item as it appears in figure referenced in adjacent Figure number column.

para0.para:
UOC appears in lower left corner of Description Column heading. Usable on codes are shown as "UOC:" in Description Column (justified left) on first line under applicable item/nomenclature. Uncoded items are applicable to all models. Examples of UOCs used in this RPSTL are:

Fabrication Instructions. Bulk materials required to manufacture items are listed in bulk material functional group of this RPSTL. Part numbers for bulk material are also referenced in Description Column of line item entry for item to be manufactured/fabricated. Detailed fabrication instructions for items source coded to be manufactured or fabricated are found in this manual .

Index Numbers. Items which have word BULK in figure column will have an index number shown in item number column. This index number is a cross-reference between NSN / P/N index work packages and bulk material list in repair parts list work package.

seqlist.item:
When NSNs or Part Numbers Are Not Known.
First. Using table of contents, determine assembly group to which item belongs. This is necessary since Figures are prepared for assembly groups and subassembly groups, and lists are divided into same groups.
Second. Find Figure covering functional group or sub functional group to which item belongs.
Third. Identify item on figure and note number(s).
Fourth. Look in repair parts list work packages for Figure and item numbers. NSNs and part numbers are on same line as associated item numbers.

When NSN Is Known.
First. If you have NSN, look in STOCK NUMBER column of NSN index work package. NSN is arranged in NIIN sequence. Note Figure and item number next to NSN.
Second. Turn to Figure and locate item number. Verify that item is one you are looking for.

When Part Number Is Known.
First. If you have P/N and not NSN, look in PART NUMBER column of P/N index work package. Identify Figure and item number.
Second. Look up item on Figure in applicable repair parts list work package.

para0.title: The Army Maintenance System MAC
para0.para: This introduction provides a general explanation of maintenance levels/classes, functions, and other information contained in MAC.

MAC (immediately following this introduction) designates overall authority and responsibility for performance of all maintenance tasks on identified end item or component. Application of maintenance tasks to end item or component shall be consistent with capacities and capabilities of designated maintenance levels/classes which are shown in MAC in column (4). Column (4) is divided into two secondary columns. These columns indicate maintenance levels/classes of 'Field' and 'Sustainment'. Each maintenance level column is further divided into two sub-columns. These sub-columns identify maintenance classes and are as follows:
Field level maintenance classes:
Crew (operator) maintenance. This is the responsibility of a using organization to perform maintenance on its assigned equipment. It normally consists of inspecting, servicing, lubricating, adjusting, and replacing parts, minor assemblies, and subassemblies. Items with a “C” (“O” for joint service reporting) in third position of Source, Maintenance, and Recoverability (SMR) code may be replaced at crew (operator) class. A code of “C” (“O” for joint service) in fourth position of SMR code indicates complete repair is authorized at crew (operator) class.
Maintainer maintenance. This is maintenance accomplished on a component, accessory, assembly, subassembly, plug-in unit, or other portion by field level units. This maintenance is performed either on system or after it is removed. An “F” in third position of SMR code indicates replacement of assemblies, subassemblies, or other components is authorized at this level. An “F” in fourth position of SMR code indicates complete repair of identified item is allowed at Maintainer class. Items repaired at this level are normally returned to user after maintenance is performed.
Sustainment level maintenance classes:
Depot. This is maintenance accomplished on a component, accessory, assembly, subassembly, plug-in unit, or other portion either on system or after it is removed. Assets to be repaired at this class are normally returned to an Army Depot or authorized contractor facility. Replace function for this class of maintenance is indicated by letter "D" or "K" appearing in third position of SMR code. A "D" or "K" appearing in fourth position of SMR code indicates complete repair is possible at depot sustainment maintenance level. Items are returned to supply system after maintenance is performed at this class.

Tools and test equipment requirements table (immediately following MAC) lists tools and test equipment (both special tools and common tool sets) required for each maintenance task as referenced from MAC.
Remarks table (immediately following tools and test equipment requirements) contains supplemental instructions and explanatory notes for a particular maintenance task.

Maintenance functions are limited to and defined as follows:
Inspect. Step-by-step instructions to determine serviceability of an item by comparing its physical, mechanical, and/or electrical characteristics with established standards through examination (e.g., by sight, sound, or feel).
Test. Step-by-step instructions to verify serviceability by measuring mechanical, pneumatic, hydraulic, or electrical characteristics of an item and comparing those characteristics with prescribed standards, e.g., load testing of lift devices or hydrostatic testing of pressure hoses. For software, to verify usability/operability/functionality of software.
Service. Step-by-step instructions to be performed periodically to keep an item in proper operating condition such as replenishing fuel, lubricants, chemical fluids, or gases.
Adjust. Step-by-step instructions to maintain or regulate, within prescribed limits, by bringing into proper position, or by setting operating characteristics to specified parameters.
Align. Step-by-step instructions to adjust specified variable elements of an item to bring about optimum or desired performance.
Calibrate. Step-by-step instructions to determine and cause corrections to be made or to be adjusted on instruments of test, measuring, and diagnostic equipment used in precision measurement. It consists of comparisons of two instruments, one of which is a certified standard of known accuracy, to detect and adjust any discrepancy in accuracy of instrument being compared.
Remove. Step-by-step instructions for taking a component off an asset to facilitate other maintenance on a different component or on same component (except for replace and repair.) For software, it is step-by-step instructions for uninstalling/removing software from a workstation or other viewing hardware.
Install. Step-by-step instructions for placing, positioning, or otherwise locating a component to make it part of a higher level end item. Install task is authorized by LPD/MAC and assigned maintenance level is shown as third position code of SMR code. For software, it is step-by-step instructions putting software on a workstation or other viewing hardware.
Replace. Step-by-step instructions for taking off an unserviceable component and putting a serviceable component in its place. Replace task is authorized by LPD/MAC and assigned maintenance level is shown as third position code of SMR code.
Repair. Step-by-step instructions for restoring an item or software to a completely serviceable or fully mission capable status. Repair task is authorized by LPD/MAC and assigned maintenance level is shown as fourth position code of SMR code. Following definitions are applicable to "repair" maintenance task: welding, grinding, riveting, straightening, facing, machining, and/or resurfacing.
Paint. Step-by-step instructions to prepare and apply coats of paint. When used with munitions, paint is applied so ammunition can be identified and protected.
Overhaul. Step-by-step instructions to restore an item to a completely serviceable/operational condition as required by maintenance standards in appropriate technical publications. Overhaul is normally highest degree of maintenance performed by Army. Overhaul does not normally return an item to a like-new condition.
Rebuild. Step-by-step instructions required for restoration of unserviceable equipment to a like new condition IAW original manufacturing standards. Rebuild is highest degree of materiel maintenance applied to Army equipment. Rebuild operation includes act of returning to zero those age measurements (e.g., hours/miles) considered in classifying Army equipment/components.
Lubricate. Step-by-step instructions for applying a material (e.g., oil or grease) to reduce friction and allow a component to operate in a more efficient manner.
Mark. Step-by-step instructions for restoring obliterated identification on an asset.
Pack. Step-by-step instructions to place an item into a container for either storage or shipment after service and other maintenance operations have been completed.
Unpack. Step-by-step instructions for removing an asset from a storage or shipping container in preparation to perform further maintenance (e.g., repair or install).
Preserve. Step-by-step instructions for treating systems and equipment whether installed or stored, to ensure a serviceable condition.
Prepare for use. Step-by-step instructions required to make an asset ready for other maintenance (e.g., remove preservatives, lubricate, etc.).
Assemble. Step-by-step instructions to join component pieces of an asset together to make a complete serviceable asset.
Disassemble. Step-by-step instructions to break down (take apart) a spare/functional group coded item to level of its least component, that is assigned an SMR code for level of maintenance under consideration (i.e., identified as maintenance significant).
Clean. Step-by-step instructions on how to remove dirt, corrosion or other contaminants from equipment. Refer to appropriate painting, lubrication, and preservation methods to restore original corrosion prevention and control methods when removed as a result of cleaning and/or when using cleaning to remove corrosion from item.
Nondestructive inspection. Step-by-step instructions on preparation and accomplishment inspections which do not destroy or damage equipment.
Radio interference suppression. Step-by-step instructions to ensure installed equipment, either communication or other electronics, does not interfere with installed communication equipment.
Place in service. Step-by-step instructions required to place an item into service that are not covered in service upon receipt work package.
Towing. Step-by-step instructions to connect one vehicle to another for purpose of having one vehicle moved through motive power of other vehicle.
Jacking. Step-by-step instructions to mechanically raise or lift a vehicle to facilitate maintenance on vehicle.
Parking. Step-by-step instructions to safely place a vehicle in a lot, ramp area or other designated location.
Mooring. Step-by-step instructions to secure a vehicle by chains, ropes or other means to protect vehicle from environmental conditions or secure for transportation.
Covering. Step-by-step instructions to place a protective wrapping over a vehicle to protect it from environmental conditions or to hide (e.g., camouflage) it.
Hoisting. Step-by-step instructions to allow a vehicle to be raised by cables or ropes through attaching points.
Sling loading. Step-by-step instructions to place a sling around a vehicle to allow it to be raised.
External power. Step-by-step instructions on how to apply electrical power from any authorized power source (e.g., external generator or facility power).
Preparation for storage. Step-by-step instructions for preparing equipment for placement into administrative, short term, and/or long-term storage.
Preparation for shipment. Step-by-step instructions for preparing equipment to be shipped or transported.
Transport. Step-by-step instructions and guidance for transporting/shipping equipment.
Arm. Step-by-step instructions on activating munitions prior to use.
Load. Step-by-step instructions for one of three tasks:
For transportation, the act of placing assets onto a transportation medium (e.g., pallet, truck, container).
For weapons/weapons systems, the act of placing munitions into weapon/weapons system.
Unload. Step-by-step instructions for one of three tasks:
For transportation, the act of removing assets from a transportation medium (e.g., pallet, truck, container).
For weapons/weapons systems, the act of removing munitions from weapon/weapons system.
Install peripheral device. Step-by-step instructions for installing peripheral devices such as printers, scanners, modems, etc.
Uninstall peripheral device. Step-by-step instructions for uninstalling peripheral devices such as printers, scanners, modems, etc.
Upgrade/patch. Step-by-step instructions for performing an upgrade to software or installing a patch to software.
Configure. Step-by-step instructions for configuring software for different uses/purposes and/or different users.
Debug. Step-by-step instructions for debugging software/correcting errors in software.

Column (1) Group Number. Column (1) lists Functional Group Code (FGC) numbers, purpose of which is to identify maintenance significant components, assemblies, subassemblies, and modules with Next Higher Assembly (NHA).
Column (2) Component/Assembly. Column (2) contains item names of components, assemblies, subassemblies, and modules for which maintenance is authorized.

Column (3) Maintenance Function. Column (3) lists functions to be performed on item listed in column (2). (For a detailed explanation of these functions, refer to maintenance functions (tasks) outlined previously.)

Column (4) Maintenance Level. Column (4) specifies each level/class of maintenance authorized to perform each function listed in column (3), by indicating man-hours required in appropriate sub-column. Man-hour figure is task time multiplied by number of maintainers required to perform that maintenance task. This time includes preparation (equipment conditions, inspections), task performance, follow-on maintenance and quality assurance (inspections) time. Crew maintenance time will be entered as task (clock) time only. If different maintenance classes perform same maintenance functions due to number or complexity of tasks, appropriate man-hour figures are to be shown for each class. Symbol designations for various maintenance levels and classes are as follows:
Field:
C Crew maintenance
F Maintainer maintenance
Sustainment:
L Specialized Repair Activity (SRA)
H Below depot maintenance
D Depot maintenance

note.trim.para: "L" maintenance class is not included in column (4) of MAC. Functions to this class of maintenance are identified by work time figure in "H" column of column (4), and an associated reference code is used in REMARKS column (6). This code is keyed to remarks and SRA complete repair application is explained there.

para0.para: Column (5) Tools and Equipment Reference Code. Column (5) specifies, by a number code, those common tool sets, kits, or outfits (not individual tools), common Test, Measurement and Diagnostic Equipment (TMDE), common tools that are not part of a set, kit, or outfit, special tools, special TMDE, and special support equipment required to perform designated function. Codes are keyed to entries in tools and test equipment table.
Column (6) Remarks Code. When applicable, this Column (6) contains a letter code, in alphabetical order, which is keyed to remarks table entries.

para.emphasis: Explanation of Columns in Tools and Test Equipment Requirements

para0.para: Column (1) Tool or Test Equipment Reference Code. Tool or test equipment reference code correlates with a code used in column (5) of MAC.
Column (2) Maintenance Level. Lowest class of maintenance authorized to use tool or test equipment.
Column (3) Nomenclature. Name or identification of tool or test equipment.
Column (4) National Stock Number (NSN). NSN of tool or test equipment.
Column (5) Tool Number. Manufacturer's part number.
Column (1) Remarks Code. Code recorded in column (6) of MAC.
Column (2) Remarks. This column lists information pertinent to maintenance task being performed as indicated in MAC.

wpidinfo.title: COMPONENTS OF END ITEM (COEI) AND BASIC ISSUE ITEMS (BII) LIST

subpara1.title: Scope
subpara1.para: This work package lists COEI and BII for Expeditionary TRICON Food Sanitation System (ETFSS) to help you inventory items for safe and efficient operation of equipment.

subpara1.title: General
subpara1.para: COEI and BII information is divided into following lists:

Components of End Item (COEI). This list is for information purposes only and is authority to requisition replacements. These items are part of ETFSS. As part of end item, these items must be with end item whenever it is issued or transferred between property accounts. Items of COEI are removed and separately packaged for transportation or shipment only when necessary. Illustrations are furnished to help you find and identify items.

Basic Issue Items (BII). These essential items are required to place ETFSS in operation, operate it, and to do emergency repairs. Although shipped separately packaged, BII must be with ETFSS during operation and when it is transferred between property accounts. Listing these items is your authority to request/requisition them for replacement based on authorization of end item by Table of Organization and Equipment/Modified Table of Organization and Equipment (TOE/MTOE). Illustrations are furnished to help you find and identify items.

subpara1.title: Explanation of Columns in COEI List and BII List
subpara1.para: Column (1) Item Number. Gives you reference number of item listed.
Column (2) National Stock Number (NSN) and Illustration. Identifies stock number of item to be used for requisitioning purposes and provides an illustration of item.

Column (3) Description, Part Number/(CAGEC). Identifies Federal item name (in all capital letters) followed by a minimum description when needed. Stowage location of COEI and BII is also included in this column. Last line below description is CAGEC (Commercial and Government Entity Code) (in parentheses) and part number.

Column (4) Usable On Code. When applicable, gives you a code if item you need is same for different models of equipment. These codes are identified below:
Code Used on
KAE Green ETFSS
KAF Tan ETFSS
Column (5) U/I. Unit of Issue (U/I) indicates physical measurement or count of item as issued per National Stock Number shown in column (2).
Column (6) Qty Rqr. Indicates quantity required.

subpara1.para: This work package lists additional items you are authorized for support of ETFSS.

subpara1.title: General
subpara1.para: This list identifies items that do not have to accompany ETFSS and that do not have to be turned in with it. These items are all authorized to you by CTA, MTOE, TDA, or JTA.

subpara1.title: Explanation of Columns in AAL
subpara1.para: Column (1) National Stock Number (NSN). Identifies stock number of item to be used for requisitioning purposes.

Column (2) Description, Part Number/(CAGEC). Identifies Federal item name (in all capital letters) followed by a minimum description when needed. Last line below description is part number and Commercial and Government Entity Code (CAGEC) (in parentheses).

Column (3) Usable On Code. When applicable, gives you a code if item you need is not same for different models of equipment. These codes are identified below:

subpara1.title: Scope
subpara1.para: This work package lists expendable and durable items that you will need to operate and maintain ETFSS. This list is for information only and is not authority to requisition listed items. These items are authorized to you by , or .

subpara1.title: Explanations of Columns in Expendable/Durable Items List
subpara1.para: Column (1) Item No. This number is assigned to entry in list and is referenced in narrative instructions to identify item (e.g., Use brake fluid (WP 0098, Item 5)).

Column (2) Level. This column identifies lowest level of maintenance that requires listed item:
C - Crew
Column (3) National Stock Number (NSN). This is NSN assigned to item which you can use to requisition it.

Column (4) Item Name, Description, Part Number/(CAGEC). This column provides other information you need to identify item. Last line below description is part number and Commercial and Government Entity Code (CAGEC) (in parentheses)
Column (5) U/I. Unit of Issue (U/I) code shows physical measurement or count of an item, such as gallon, dozen, gross, etc.

subpara1.title: SCOPE
subpara1.para: This work package lists all common and special tools, supplements, fixtures needed to maintain the Expeditionary TRICON Food Sanitation System.

subpara1.title: Explanation of Columns in Tool Identification List
subpara1.para: Column (1) Item No. This number is assigned to entry in list and is referenced in initial setup to identify item (e.g., Extractor (WP 0090, item 32)).
Column (2) Item Name. This column lists item by noun nomenclature and other descriptive features (e.g., Gauge, belt tension).
Column (3) National Stock Number (NSN). This is National Stock Number (NSN) assigned to item; use it to requisition item.

Column (4) Part Number/(CAGEC). Indicates primary number used by manufacturer (individual, company, firm, corporation, or Government activity) which controls design and characteristics of item by means of its engineering drawings, specifications, standards, and inspection requirements to identify an item or range of items. Manufacturer's Commercial and Government Entity Code (CAGEC) is also included.
Column (5) Reference. This column identifies authorizing supply catalog, components list, or RPSTL for items listed in this work package.

subpara1.title: Scope
subpara1.para: This work package includes a list of all mandatory replacement parts referenced in initial setups and procedures including those referenced in Preventive Maintenance Checks and Services. These are items that must be replaced during maintenance whether they have failed or not. This includes items based on usage intervals such as miles, time, rounds fired, etc.

subpara1.title: Explanation of Columns in the Mandatory Replacement Parts List
subpara1.para: Column (1) Item No. This number is assigned to entry in list and is referenced in narrative instructions to identify item (e.g., Use O-ring (WP 0098, item 5)).
Column (2) Part Number / (CAGEC). Identifies part number of item and manufacturer's Commercial and Government Entity Code (CAGEC) to be used for requisitioning purposes.
Column (3) National Stock Number (NSN) Identifies stock number of item to be used for requisitioning purposes.
Column (4) Nomenclature. The official names of equipment as shown in FEDLOG H6 listing.
Column (5) Qty. Indicates quantity required.
